      "acceptanceCriteria": "CFD solver must have documented version control, regression testing, and release notes consistent with MRL 2 requirements.",
      "rationale": "ANSYS Fluent 2024 R1 is employed under an institutional software quality plan that includes version-controlled configuration files, automated regression tests for benchmark cases, and a formal release verification checklist. All SQA artifacts are archived and traceable to the simulation run IDs used in this assessment."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Numerical code verification",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Solver must demonstrate correct implementation of governing equations through at least one benchmark verification case relevant to internal rotating flow.",
      "rationale": "Code verification was established via the Taylor-Couette flow benchmark, where analytical solutions for laminar and transitional regimes are available. Normalized RMS error between solver output and analytical solution was 0.31%, confirming correct numerical implementation of the incompressible Navier-Stokes equations with rotating reference frame treatment."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Discretization error",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "GCI for primary QoI (wall shear stress, hemolysis index) must be less than 5% on the medium mesh used for production runs.",
      "rationale": "A three-level mesh refinement study (coarse: 4.2M cells, medium: 11.7M cells, fine: 31.4M cells) was conducted. GCI values for wall shear stress and scalar hemolysis index were 4.8% and 2.1% respectively on the medium mesh, satisfying the 5% threshold. Production simulations use the medium mesh."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Test conditions",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Experimental test conditions used for validation must be documented and shown to correspond to the simulated operating envelope within stated uncertainty bounds.",
      "rationale": "The experimental conditions from the FDA benchmark program are documented in peer-reviewed publications. Flow rates (2–6 L/min) and rotational speeds (2000–3500 RPM) match the CFD boundary conditions within ±2% of nominal values. Temperature and fluid viscosity are reported and reproduced in the blood analog fluid model."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Output comparison",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Quantitative comparison metric (normalized error or validation metric) must be computed and shown to fall within the pre-specified acceptance band.",
      "rationale": "Relative hemolysis index predictions were compared against experimental measurements at all five operating points. Normalized errors ranged from 3.1% to 12.7%, with a mean of 8.3%. All values fall within the pre-specified ±15% acceptance band. Validation metric computed per ASME V&V 20 framework."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Relevance of the quantities of interest",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "The QoIs used in validation (hemolysis index, shear stress) must directly correspond to the QoIs used in the clinical decision (relative hemolysis RH).",
      "rationale": "The primary QoI in the COU is the relative hemolysis index RH, computed from the power-law hemolysis model applied to predicted shear stress and exposure time. The validation QoI is the same scalar quantity derived from experimental RBC damage measurements. Direct correspondence between validation and decision QoIs is established."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Relevance of the validation activities to the COU",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
